  "prompt": "Are there any satellites recovered from space?",
  "response": "Yes, there have been instances where spacecraft or satellites have been recovered after being launched into space. One notable example is the retrieval of film canisters from reconnaissance satellites during the Cold War era. For example, the United States' Corona program used satellites that ejected film canisters containing reconnaissance photos back to Earth. These canisters were often captured mid-air by aircraft or retrieved after landing. \n\nAdditionally, the Space Shuttle missions were capable of capturing and returning satellites to Earth. One famous case is the retrieval of the Solar Maximum Mission (SMM) satellite by the Space Shuttle Challenger in 1984. The SMM was repaired and then redeployed during the same mission.\n\nThese examples show that recovery of objects from space has been achieved in specific, usually highly planned, missions.",
